data.content:
In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. Every synchronous call in your repository will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

**What breaks:**

| Sync call (now fails) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

**Timeline of this change:**
- **EF Core 9** — Cosmos provider started throwing on sync calls by default, but offered a `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` warning you could suppress.
- **EF Core 10 (.NET 10)** — opt-in still worked but was marked `[Obsolete]`.
- **EF Core 11 (.NET 11)** — opt-in removed. No workaround; sync I/O is gone.

**Fix — convert to async throughout:**

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

The Cosmos DB SDK is async-only under the hood, so this aligns your code with what was always actually happening. You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your callers (controllers, services, etc.).
